result.execSummary:
The defendant Tracy Lynn Lambert was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Violate/Harassment Restraining Order - Injunction, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 813.125(7).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

9:50 AM Defendant Tracy Lynn Lambert in court.  Attorney Chad C La Lor in court for State of Wisconsin.  Attorney John E Swanberg in court for Tracy Lynn Lambert. State notes defendant to plead to sole count. State recites agreement of 45 days jail imposed and stayed for 1 year probation. Conditions of probation include serve 1 day jail with credit for 1 day served, no contact with victim, comply with all programming as deemed necessary and pay a $100 fine plus costs. State has complied with Victim's Rights. Defendant pleads no contest. Attorney Swanberg stipulates to a factual basis. Court accepts the Defendant's plea and finds that the Defendant's plea has been freely, voluntarily and intelligently made. The Defendant understands all the rights she is waiving by her plea. The Defendant is found guilty and Judgment of Conviction is entered.

Court imposes for sole count, 45 days jail imposed and stayed for 1 year probation. Conditions of probation include serve 1 day jail with credit for 1 day, time served, no contact with victim, comply with all programming as deemed necessary and pay a $100 fine plus costs.
